To solve this problem, we will use the law of conservation of energy. This means that the heat gained by gold will be equal to the heat lost by water.

Let's denote:

mWater = mass of water = 10 g;
cWater = specific heat of water = 4.18 J/g°C;

mGold = mass of gold = 3 g;
cGold = specific heat of gold = 0.128 J/g°C;

TWater_initial = initial temperature of the water = 159°C;
TGold_initial = initial temperature of the gold = 15.2°C;

T_final = final temperature of the system.

We know that: heat gained = heat lost

So, mGold * cGold * (T_final - TGold_initial) = mWater * cWater * (TWater_initial - T_final)

Re-arranging to find T_final:

T_final = (mGold * cGold * TGold_initial + mWater * cWater * TWater_initial) / ( mGold * cGold + mWater * cWater)

Substituting the known values in:

T_final = (3 g * 0.128 J/g°C * 15.2°C + 10 g * 4.18 J/g°C * 159°C) / (3 g * 0.128 J/g°C + 10 g * 4.18 J/g°C)

T_final = 144.9°C

